Bolivia and Chile will continue the dialogue at some point, but after this it will be extremely difficult to negotiate.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodr<0xC3><0xAD>guez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, disagrees with the view that the court's decision was made unusually quickly.
Monday will bring Bolivia an “unusual opportunity to start a new era in relations with Chile” and an opportunity to “end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefit,” he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales – still one of the most beloved presidents in Latin America – used the maritime issue as a political crutch.
