John Edward: The language skills that the world's citizens need
Scottish independent schools have a tradition of academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with another package of outstanding exam results, with added weight given to individual and joint achievements in sport, the arts, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further education and higher education, a career they want and make them citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement the aforementioned school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a favorite and desired subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his native language, it goes to his heart.”
This statement is a strong reminder that we cannot use only English if we want to build trust and relationships with people from other countries.
The latest results of this year's final exams show that the highest marks in languages were achieved by participants of independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages received excellent grades.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools show that 72% of students received an excellent grade in Mandarin, while 72% of students who learn German, 69% of students who learn French and 63% of students who learn Spanish also received the highest possible grade.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a key skill that children and young people will surely need in the future.
Today, languages as elective subjects are considered as important as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculum of independent schools, as well as in other places.
A 2014 UK Employment and Skills Commission survey found that 17% of employers are unable to fill jobs due to a lack of language skills workforce.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming an imperative for preparing young people for careers.
As more and more jobs require language skills, these skills are crucial in a globalised world.
Regardless of the choice of career, people who have learned to speak a foreign language in the future will feel the benefits of such a long-term skill.
A person who speaks several languages can communicate directly with foreigners, and this gives him an advantage over the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults, 75% of respondents in the UK do not know a foreign language well enough to communicate in it, and French is the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage of respondents, 15% to be exact.
Therefore, investing in language learning is very important for today’s children.
If children learn more languages, especially the languages of developing countries, they will have more opportunities to find good employment.
In Scotland, every school offers a variety of languages.
Some schools will include classical, modern languages in their curriculum, while others will opt for languages considered to be most important in the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interests, independent schools will always have a variety of choices, as well as teaching staff who are proficient in the field.
Scottish independent schools provide children with an environment in which learning will prepare and equip them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
One cannot ignore the fact that in today's global business world, language skills are very important for the future of every country, so this must also be reflected in education.
Thus, knowledge of modern languages should really be seen as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer language choice, diversity and excellence to young Scots.
I'll be honest with you.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Independent Schools Council.
