North Korea says ‘no chance’ of unilateral disarmament without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that further sanctions increase mistrust of the United States and there was no chance that North Korea would unilaterally disarm and give up its nuclear weapons in such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the UN General Assembly last year that North Korea had taken "significant measures of good will," such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear testing station and making a decision to halt the development of nuclear technology and weapons.
“However, we have not received a satisfactory response from the United States,” he added.
“If we don’t have confidence in the United States, we don’t have faith in our national security either. Under such circumstances, there is no chance that we will be the first to unilaterally disarm.”
While Ri echoed North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “gradual” approach to denuclearization that would gradually lift sanctions on North Korea, his statement is significant because he did not reject unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first meeting in the history of the current US president and the leader of North Korea in Singapore on June 12, when Kim promised to work on the “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula,” while Trump guaranteed the security of North Korea.
North Korea wants to officially end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the U.S. has made it conditional on Pyongyang giving up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also ignored calls to reduce strict international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists that denuclearization be carried out first and increases the pressure through sanctions to forcefully achieve its goal, and even opposes the 'declaration of the end of the war'," Ri added.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is just a delusion of people who know nothing about us.
The main problem is that the continuation of sanctions increases mistrust."
Ri did not mention whether there were plans for a second meeting between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. president spoke about earlier this week at the United Nations.
But the minister noted that Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in had held as many as three meetings in the past five months, adding: “If South Korea had asked for denuclearization, not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have come to such a halt.”
Whatever the case, Rio’s tone was very different from last year when he addressed the UN General Assembly and said that targeting the continental United States with missiles was inevitable after the evil President Trump called Kim a “man-made missile” on a suicide mission.
Trump, who threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea last year at the United Nations, praised Kim for his courage to disarm, but added that there was still much work to be done and that sanctions must remain in place until North Korea denuclearizes.
Trump said on Wednesday there was no timeline for denuclearization, adding: "It doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years or five months."
China and Russia have expressed the view that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The implementation of Security Council sanctions must strictly continue until there is complete, final and verified denuclearization.”
