Students at Harvard take a course that teaches how to have a good rest
A new course at Harvard University has allowed all students to get a good night’s sleep in an attempt to combat the increasingly widespread culture of learning alongside caffeine and sleepless nights.
The academician found that students at the world's best university often have no idea about the basics of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep science at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has designed what he believes is the first course of its kind in the United States.
He came up with the idea for the course after giving a speech on the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
At the end of the lecture, a girl came up to me and said, “Why did I only find out this now, in my senior year of college?”
She said no one had told her how important sleep was, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is being held for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleep habits help academic and sports success and generally improve health.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s health service, said the university decided to introduce the course after students were found to have a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course consists of a series of interactive assignments.
One of these tasks involves a picture of a student dormitory where students have to click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books to find out what the effects of caffeine and light are, how lack of sleep affects success, and how important the sleep routine is.
During the lecture, students also learn how long-term lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
After that, a map of the campus with interactive icons is displayed, which encourages students to think about their daily routine.
“We know that the behavior of students will not change immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know, how cigarettes affect health,” Professor Czeisler added.
The culture of pride in all-night learning before the exam still exists, says the professor, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students prove that lack of sleep is an increasing problem.
The professor says that the secret weapon of students against stress, exhaustion and anxiety should be a good and quality sleep. Sleep also helps in the fight against weight gain, because lack of sleep affects the brain, puts it in a state of starvation and causes constant hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old chemistry and biology student from California, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending his first year of Harvard.
He says the course opened his eyes and inspired him to extend the course to the entire campus.
As a next step, it plans to ask all graduate students to complete a similar course of study before joining a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends students to turn on the alarm during sleep, as well as during waking. They must be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by the screens of electronic devices, as well as LED lights that can disrupt the circadian rhythm and cause sleep problems.
