What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it achieved anything in terms of poverty reduction?
This Saturday, New York will host the Global Citizen Festival, an annual music event with an impressive roster of stars and an equally impressive mission – ending poverty in the world.
For the seventh year in a row, the Global Citizen Festival will bring together tens of thousands of people in Central Park to enjoy not only the performances of stars such as Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also raise awareness of the real goal of the event, ending extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which began in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international advocacy group hoping to end poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
To get a free ticket to the event (unless they were willing to pay for a VIP ticket), concertgoers had to perform a series of tasks or “actions” such as volunteering, sending emails to a world leader, making phone calls, or any other meaningful means of raising awareness of their goal of ending poverty.
But how successful is Global Citizen, given that it has 12 years left to achieve its goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert the right way to convince people to demand a call to action, or just another case of so-called “clictivism” – where people feel that signing an online petition or tweeting really changes something?
Since 2011, Global Citizen claims to have recorded more than 19 million “actions” by its supporters that sought to achieve a range of different goals.
He said the actions were an incentive for world leaders to announce commitments and policies that would lead to more than $37 billion in spending that would impact the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
