World Wide Web inventor plans to launch new internet to take over Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a new company that aims to become a competitor to Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of this technology legend, Inrupt, is a company that is developing on the basis of Berners-Lee's open platform Solid.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and the people who will be allowed to access certain information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intent behind Inrupt was "world domination".
“We have to do it now,” he said, referring to the startup.
“This is a historic moment.”
The app uses Solid’s technology to allow people to create their own “personal online data storage” or POD.
It can contain contact lists, to-do lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack, and Spotify are all available on one browser at a time.
What is unique when it comes to personal online data storage is that it’s up to who can access which information in full to the user.
The company calls this “personal empowerment through data.”
The idea for Inrupt, according to company CEO John Bruce, is for the company to provide resources, processes, and the right skills to help make Solid accessible to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform acquired by IBM, several engineers who have signed a contract to work on the project, and a community of volunteer developers.
Starting this week, developers from around the world were able to build their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team are not talking to Facebook and Google about whether or not they will introduce a complete change in which all of their business models would be completely reversed overnight.
“We’re not asking for their permission.”
