New data on red tide: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission (FWC) shows a general decrease in red tide concentrations in parts of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, heterogeneous algal bloom conditions are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier <0xCC><0xB6> counties, indicating a decrease in concentrations.
The red tide stretches about 130 miles along the coast from the northern part of Pinellas County to the southern part of Lee County.
Flowering areas can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places compared to last week.
A red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
In the past week, medium concentrations have been recorded in Pinellas County or in the adjacent offshore area, low to high concentrations in the Hillsborough County offshore area, common to high concentrations in Manatee County, common to high concentrations in Sarasota County or the adjacent offshore area, common to high concentrations in Le Charlotte County, and high concentrations in the Colley County offshore area.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to be reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
Respiratory distress has not been reported in northwest Florida over the past week.
